Interview_Prep_Agent.skills
World-class interview preparation agent for mock interviews, STAR responses, and brutally honest feedback.

Quick Start
Main Capabilities
# Core Tool 1
conduct_mock --type behavioral|technical|case_study|culture_fit --role target_role --difficulty easy|medium|hard

# Core Tool 2
craft_STAR_response --question "Tell me about a time..." --situation context --task challenge --action steps --result metrics

# Core Tool 3
debrief_performance --mock_session completed --feedback strengths weaknesses delivery content --score 1_10

Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

Behavioral interview preparation (STAR/CAR method)
Technical interview coaching (system design, coding, case studies)
Culture fit and values alignment responses
Salary expectation framing and deflection
"Tell me about yourself" narrative crafting (2-minute pitch)
Weakness questions handled authentically
Situational judgment and hypothetical scenario responses
Body language and delivery coaching
Post-interview follow-up strategy
Red flag identification in interviewer behavior

Methodologies & Frameworks
Response Methods: STAR (Situation, Task, Action, Result), CAR (Challenge, Action, Result), PAR (Problem, Action, Result)
Interview Types: Phone screen, Behavioral, Technical, Panel, Case study, Culture fit, Executive
Question Banks: Top 50 behavioral questions, Role-specific technical questions, Curveball questions
Evaluation: Mock interview scoring rubric (Content, Delivery, Relevance, Confidence)
Research: Company research framework (mission, recent news, competitor landscape, interviewer LinkedIn)
Negotiation: Salary deflection techniques, Counter-offer frameworks, Total compensation evaluation

Reference Documentation
1. Behavioral Interview Mastery
Comprehensive guide covering:
- Top 20 behavioral questions with STAR templates
- Leadership stories, Conflict stories, Failure stories, Success stories
- How to select the RIGHT story for each question
- Keeping responses 90-120 seconds (structured but not robotic)
- The "So what?" test — every answer must have impact/learning

2. Technical Interview Strategies
Complete preparation library:
- System design: framework-based approach (requirements, design, trade-offs)
- Coding interviews: problem-solving narration, edge cases, complexity analysis
- Case studies: structured frameworks (profitability, market entry, product launch)
- Product sense: customer-first thinking, metrics definition, prioritization

3. Hidden Interview Skills
Technical reference with:
- First 30 seconds: Handshake, eye contact, energy level set the tone
- Questions to ASK the interviewer (shows preparation and curiosity)
- Reading the room: When to elaborate vs. when to be concise
- "Tell me about yourself" = your 2-minute elevator pitch, NOT your life story
- Thank you email within 24 hours (brief, specific to conversation)

Interview Patterns
Pattern 1: The STAR Power Response
Structured behavioral answer:
- Situation: "In my role at [Company], we faced [specific challenge]..." (2 sentences)
- Task: "I was responsible for [specific ownership]..." (1 sentence)
- Action: "I [specific actions, using 'I' not 'we']..." (3-4 sentences, most detail here)
- Result: "This resulted in [quantified outcome]..." (1-2 sentences with numbers)
- Total: 90-120 seconds maximum

Pattern 2: Mock Interview Session
Realistic practice simulation:
- Pre-brief: Target role, company, interview stage
- 5-7 questions progressively harder
- Timer per response (2 min max)
- Real-time notes on filler words, eye contact descriptions, structure
- Post-session debrief with scores and specific improvement areas
- Record (voice memo) and listen back for self-awareness

Pattern 3: Company Research Blitz
30-minute pre-interview preparation:
- Company: Mission statement, recent funding/earnings, product launches
- Role: Job description keyword analysis, team structure, reporting line
- Interviewer: LinkedIn profile, recent posts, shared connections
- Industry: Recent trends, competitors, challenges
- Prepare 3-5 thoughtful questions that show genuine interest
- Prepare your "Why this company?" answer with specific evidence

Best Practices
Preparation
- Every answer needs a metric or measurable outcome — vague stories don't land
- Prepare 8-10 versatile stories that cover: leadership, conflict, failure, ambiguity, teamwork, initiative
- Practice out loud, not just in your head — speaking and thinking are different skills
- Research shows candidates who ask good questions are rated higher than those who just answer well
- Mock interviews with real people (or AI) reduce anxiety by 40-60%

Delivery
- Pause before answering — 2-3 seconds of thoughtful silence beats immediate rambling
- "I" not "we" — they're hiring YOU, show YOUR contribution
- Match your energy to the interviewer's energy + 10% (mirror and slightly elevate)
- Filler words (um, like, you know) are normal but trainable — reduce, don't eliminate
- End every answer cleanly — don't trail off or add "yeah..." at the end

Mistakes
- Badmouthing previous employers — instant red flag, no exceptions
- Answers longer than 2 minutes — you've lost them
- Not having questions prepared — signals low interest
- Memorized scripted answers — sound robotic, fall apart with follow-ups
- Failing to connect your experience to THEIR needs — always bridge back

